</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	Long-lived assets &#8211;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	We assess property and equipment for impairment only when circumstances (as specified in ASC 360-10-35,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	Property, Plant, and Equipment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	) indicate an impairment may exist.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our determination is based upon, among other things, our estimates of the amount of future net cash flows to be generated by the long-lived asset (Level 3 inputs) and our estimates of the current fair value of the asset.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:5.24%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:5.24%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Significant judgment is required in estimating such cash flows.&nbsp;&nbsp;Adverse changes in such estimates of future net cash flows or estimates of fair value could result in an inability to recover the carrying value of the long-lived asset, thereby possibly requiring an impairment charge to be recognized in the future.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not assess our property and equipment for impairment unless certain impairment indicators specified in ASC Topic 360-10-35 are present.&nbsp;&nbsp;We did not evaluate any long-lived assets for impairment during 2015 because no such impairment indicators were present.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:5.24%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:5.24%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL';FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL';FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	Income taxes &#8211;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	We recognize deferred taxes for future tax effects of temporary differences between financial and income tax reporting.&nbsp;&nbsp;Deferred income tax assets and liabilities for each tax-paying jurisdiction in which we operate are netted and presented as either a noncurrent deferred income tax asset or liability, as applicable.&nbsp;&nbsp;While we have considered future taxable income and ongoing prudent and feasible tax planning strategies in assessing the need for a valuation allowance, it is possible that in the future we may change our estimate of the amount of the deferred income tax assets that would more-likely-than-not be realized in the future resulting in an adjustment to the deferred income tax asset valuation allowance that would either increase or decrease, as applicable, reported net income in the period the change in estimate was made.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:5.24%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:5.24%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We record a reserve for uncertain tax positions in accordance with the provisions of ASC Topic 740,
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Income Taxes
</FONT>
	, for tax positions where we believe it is more-likely-than-not our position will not prevail with the applicable tax authorities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our reserve for uncertain tax positions is nil for each of 2014 and 2015.
</P>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	Accruals
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	&#8211;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	We record accruals for environmental, legal and other contingencies and commitments when estimated future expenditures associated with the contingencies become probable, and we can reasonably estimate the amounts of the future expenditures.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, new information may become available to us, or circumstances (such as applicable laws and regulations) may change, thereby resulting in an increase or decrease in the amount we are required to accrue for such matters (and, therefore, a corresponding decrease or increase of our reported net income in the period of such change.)
</FONT>

<EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<A NAME="FIS_MARKET_RISK"></A>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:11.77%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ITEM&#160;7A.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	QUANTITATIVE AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	General
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are exposed to market risk from changes in raw materials prices.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Raw materials.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We will occasionally enter into short term commodity-related raw material supply arrangements to mitigate the impact of future increases in commodity-related raw material costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not have long-term supply agreements for our raw material requirements because either we believe the risk of unavailability of those raw materials is low and we believe the downside risk of price volatility to be too great or because long-term supply agreements for those materials are generally not available.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not engage in commodity raw material hedging programs.
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>
<A NAME="FIS_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES"></A>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">

<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:11.85%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:5.24%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Evaluation of Disclosure Controls and Procedures.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	We maintain disclosure controls and procedures which, as defined in Exchange Act Rule 13a-15(e), means controls and other procedures that are designed to ensure that information required to be disclosed in the reports that we file or submit to the SEC under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#8220;Act&#8221;), is recorded, processed, summarized and reported, within the time periods specified in the SEC&#8217;s rules and forms. Disclosure controls and procedures include, without limitation, controls and procedures designed to ensure that information we are required to disclose in the reports that we file or submit to the SEC under the Act is accumulated and communicated to our management, including our principal executive officer and our principal financial officer, or persons performing similar functions, as appropriate to allow timely decisions to be made regarding required disclosure. Our management with the participation of David A. Bowers, our Vice Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer, and James W. Brown, our Vice President, Chief Financial Officer and Controller, have evaluated the design and operating effectiveness of our disclosure controls and procedures as of December&#160;31, 2015. Based upon their evaluation, these executive officers have concluded that our disclosure controls and procedures are effective as of the date of such evaluation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:5.24%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Management&#8217;s Report on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	.&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	Our management is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting which, as defined in Exchange Act Rule 13a-15(f)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	, means a process designed by, or under the supervision of, our principal executive and principal financial officers, or persons performing similar functions, and effected by our board of directors, management and other personnel, to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and includes those policies and procedures that:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:5.24%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:3.85%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">

	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:3.85%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL';FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL';FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	Pertain to the maintenance of records that in reasonable detail accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of our assets.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>

<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL';FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:3.85%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:5.24%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our evaluation of the effectiveness of our internal control over financial reporting is based upon the framework established in Internal Control &#8211; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission in 2013 (commonly referred to as the &#8220;2013 COSO&#8221; framework).&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on our evaluation under that framework, our management has concluded that our internal control over financial reporting was effective as of December 31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:5.24%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	This annual report does not include an attestation report of our registered public accounting firm regarding internal control over financial reporting.&nbsp;&nbsp;Management&#8217;s report was not subject to attestation by our registered public accounting firm pursuant to rules of the SEC that permit us to provide only management&#8217;s report in this annual report.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:5.24%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Changes in Internal Control Over Financial Reporting
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;There have been no changes in our internal control over financial reporting during the quarter ended December 31, 2015 that have materially affected, or are reasonably likely to materially affect, our internal control over financial reporting.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	-&#160;21&#160;-

<A NAME="FIS_AUDITORS_OPINION"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU25">
</A>
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM_REPORT_OF_INDEPENDENT_REGISTERED_PUBLIC">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM_REPORT_OF_INDEPENDENT_REGISTERED_PUBLIC">
</A>
	R
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	EPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	To the Board of Directors and Stockholders of CompX International Inc.:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In our opinion, the consolidated financial statements listed in the accompanying index present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of CompX International Inc. and its Subsidiaries at December&#160;31, 2014 and 2015, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for each of the three years in the period ended December&#160;31, 2015 in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.&nbsp;&nbsp;These financial statements are the responsibility of the Company&#8217;s management.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements based on our audits.&nbsp;&nbsp;We conducted our audits of these statements in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States).&nbsp;&nbsp;Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement.&nbsp;&nbsp;An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements, assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, and evaluating the overall financial statement presentation.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	As discussed in Note 12 to the consolidated financial statements, the Company changed the classification and presentation of deferred income taxes in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	/s/PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP
</P>

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PT;PADDING-RIGHT:0.75PT;PADDING-TOP:0.75PT;WIDTH:1%; BORDER-BOTTOM:DOUBLE 2.5PT TRANSPARENT;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:1PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
</EFX_STOCKHOLDERS_EQUITY>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	See accompanying Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	F-8
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage34"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	COMPX INTERNATIONAL INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES
</P>
<EFX_NOTES_TO_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT>
<A NAME="FIS_NOTES_TO_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM_NOTES_TO_CONSOLIDATED_FINANCIAL_STATEMEN">
</A>
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM_NOTES_TO_CONSOLIDATED_FINANCIAL_STATEMEN">
</A>
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	December&#160;31, 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:2PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:13.08%;TEXT-INDENT:-13.08%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 1
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	&#8211;
</FONT>
	Summary of significant accounting policies:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:13.08%;TEXT-INDENT:-13.08%;FONT-SIZE:6PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Organization.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We (NYSE MKT: CIX) are 87% owned by NL Industries, Inc. (NYSE: NL) at December 31, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;We manufacture and sell component products (security products and recreational marine components).&nbsp;&nbsp;At December 31, 2015,&#160;Valhi, Inc. (NYSE: VHI) owns 83% of NL&#8217;s outstanding common stock and a wholly-owned subsidiary of Contran Corporation owns 93% of Valhi&#8217;s outstanding common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;All of Contran&#8217;s outstanding voting stock is held by a family trust established for the benefit of Lisa K. Simmons and Serena Simmons Connelly and their children, for which Ms. Simmons and Ms. Connelly are co-trustees, or is held directly by Ms. Simmons and Ms. Connelly or entities related to them.&nbsp;&nbsp;Consequently, Ms. Simmons and Ms. Connelly may be deemed to control Contran, Valhi, NL and us.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Unless otherwise indicated, references in this report to &#8220;we,&#8221; &#8220;us,&#8221; or &#8220;our&#8221; refer to CompX International Inc. and its subsidiaries, taken as a whole.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Management estimates.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	In preparing our financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;) we are required to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at each balance sheet date and the reported amounts of our revenues and expenses during each reporting period.&nbsp;&nbsp;Actual results may differ significantly from previously estimated amounts under different assumptions or conditions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Principles of consolidation
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Our consolidated financial statements include the accounts of CompX International Inc. and our wholly-owned subsidiaries.&nbsp;&nbsp;We eliminate all material intercompany accounts and balances.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Fiscal year.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Our fiscal year end is always the Sunday closest to December&#160;31, and our operations are reported on a 52 or 53-week fiscal year.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each of the years ended December&#160;31, 2013 and 2014 consisted of 52 weeks.&nbsp;&nbsp;The year ended December 31, 2015 consisted of 53 weeks.&nbsp;&nbsp;For presentation purposes, annual and quarterly information in the consolidated financial statements and accompanying notes are presented as ended on March 31, June 30, September 30 and December 31, as applicable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Cash and cash equivalents
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We classify as cash and cash equivalents, bank time deposits and government and commercial notes and bills with original maturities of three months or less.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Net sales
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	. &#160;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We record sales when products are shipped and title and other risks and rewards of ownership have passed to the customer.&nbsp;&nbsp;Amounts charged to customers for shipping and handling are not material.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales are stated net of price, early payment and distributor discounts and volume rebates.&nbsp;&nbsp;We report any tax assessed by a governmental authority that we collect from our customers that is both imposed on and concurrent with our revenue producing activities (such as sales and use taxes) on a net basis (meaning we do not recognize these taxes either in our revenues or in our costs and expenses).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Accounts receivable.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We provide an allowance for doubtful accounts for known and estimated potential losses rising from our sales to customers based on a periodic review of these accounts.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	F-9
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage35"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU32">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Inventories and cost of sales
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We state inventories at the lower of cost or market, ne
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	t of allowance for obsolete and slow-moving inventories
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We generally base inventory costs for all inventory categories on average cost that approximates the first-in, first-out method
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Inventories include the costs for raw materials, the cost to manufac
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	ture the raw materials into finished goods and overhead
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Depending on the inventory&#8217;s stage of completion, our manufacturing costs can include the costs of packing and finishing, utilities, maintenance and depreciation, shipping and handling, and salaries
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	and benefits associated with our manufacturing process
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We alloca
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	te fixed manufacturing overhead costs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	based on normal production capacity
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Unallocated overhead costs resulting from periods with abnormally low production levels are charged to expense as
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	incurred
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	As inventory is sold to third parties, we recognize the cost of sales in the same period that the sale occurs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We periodically review our inventory for estimated obsolescence or instances when inventory is no longer marketable for its intended
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	use, and we record any write-down
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	equal to the difference between the cost of inventory and its estimated net realizable value
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	based on assumptions about alternative uses, market conditions and other factors.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Selling, general and administrative expenses; advertising costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Selling, general and administrative expenses include costs related to marketing, sales, distribution, research and development and administrative functions such as accounting, treasury and finance, and includes costs for salaries and benefits, travel and entertainment, promotional materials and professional fees.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expense advertising and research and development costs as incurred.&nbsp;&nbsp;Advertising costs were not significant in 2013, 2014 or 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Goodwill.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Goodwill represents the excess of cost over fair value of individual net assets acquired in business combinations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Goodwill is not subject to periodic amortization.&nbsp;&nbsp;We evaluate goodwill for impairment annually or when circumstances indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the third quarter of 2013, we adopted Financial Accounting Standards Board ASU No. 2011-08 (now codified in ASC 350-20-35), which provided new guidance on testing goodwill for impairment.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new guidance allows an entity to first assess qualitative factors to determine whether it is necessary to perform the two-step quantitative goodwill impairment test.&nbsp;&nbsp;An entity is no longer required to calculate the fair value of a reporting unit unless the entity determines, based on a qualitative assessment considering the totality of relevant events and circumstances, that it is more likely than not that the fair value of the reporting unit is less than its carrying amount.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Note 5.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Property and equipment; depreciation expense
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We state property and equipment, including purchased computer software for internal use, at cost.&nbsp;&nbsp;We compute depreciation of property and equipment for financial reporting purposes principally by the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of 15 to 40 years for buildings and 3 to 20 years for equipment and software.&nbsp;&nbsp;We use accelerated depreciation methods for income tax purposes, as permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depreciation expense was $3.2 million in 2013 and $3.5 million in 2014 and 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon sale or retirement of an asset, the related cost and accumulated depreciation are removed from the accounts and any gain or loss is recognized in income currently.&nbsp;&nbsp;Expenditures for maintenance, repairs and minor renewals are expensed; expenditures for major improvements are capitalized.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We perform impairment tests when events or changes in circumstances indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable.&nbsp;&nbsp;We consider all relevant factors.&nbsp;&nbsp;We perform the impairment test by comparing the estimated future undiscounted cash flows associated with the asset to the asset&#8217;s net carrying value to determine if impairment exists.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Employee benefit plans.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We maintain various defined contribution plans in which we make contributions based on matching or other formulas.&nbsp;&nbsp;Defined contribution plan expense approximated $2.0 million in 2013, $2.3 million in 2014 and $2.4 million in 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Self-insurance. &#160;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We are partially self-insured for workers&#8217; compensation and certain employee health benefits and self-insured for most environmental issues.&nbsp;&nbsp;We purchase coverage in order to limit our exposure to any significant levels of workers&#8217; compensation or employee health benefit claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;We accrue self-insured losses based upon estimates of the aggregate liability for uninsured claims incurred using certain actuarial assumptions followed in the insurance industry and our own historical claims experience.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU33">
</A>
	Income taxes
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	. &#160;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We, and our parent NL, are members of the Contran Tax Group.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have been and currently are a part of the consolidated tax returns filed by Contran for U.S. federal purposes as well as for certain U.S. state jurisdictions.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a member of the Contran Tax Group, we are jointly and severally liable for the federal
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	F-10
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage36"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	income tax liability of Contran and the other companies included in the Contran Tax Group for all periods in which we are included in the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Contran Tax Group.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Note 10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	As a member of the Contran Tax Group, we are a party to a tax sharing agreement which provides that we compute our provision for U.S. income taxes on a separate-company basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant to the tax sharing agreement, we make payments to or receive payments from NL in amounts we would have paid to or received from the U.S. Internal Revenue Service or the applicable state tax authority had we not been a member of the Contran Tax Group.&nbsp;&nbsp;The separate company provisions and payments are computed using the tax elections made by Contran. We made net cash payments for income taxes to NL of $14.1 million in 2013, $4.4 million in 2014 and $4.7 million in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Deferred income tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the expected future tax consequences of temporary differences between the income tax and financial reporting carrying amounts of assets and liabilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Deferred income tax assets and liabilities for each tax-paying jurisdiction in which we operate are netted and presented as either a noncurrent deferred income tax asset or liability, as applicable.&nbsp;&nbsp;We periodically evaluate our deferred tax assets in the various taxing jurisdictions in which we operate and adjust any related valuation allowance based on the estimate of the amount of deferred tax assets which we believe do not meet the more-likely-than-not recognition criteria.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Notes 7 and 12.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We record a reserve for uncertain tax positions for tax positions where we believe it is more-likely-than-not our position will not prevail with the applicable tax authorities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our reserve for uncertain tax positions was nil in each of 2014 and 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Earnings per share
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Basic earnings per share of common stock is computed using the weighted average number of common shares actually outstanding during each period.&nbsp;&nbsp;Diluted earnings per share of common stock includes the impact of outstanding dilutive stock options.&nbsp;&nbsp; There were no outstanding stock options during 2013, 2014 or 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:13.08%;TEXT-INDENT:-13.08%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 2
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	&#8211;
</FONT>
	Business and geographic segments:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our operating segments are defined as components of our continuing operations about which separate financial information is available that is regularly evaluated by our chief operating decision maker in determining how to allocate resources and in assessing performance.&nbsp;&nbsp;At December 31, 2015, we had two operating segments &#8211; Security Products and Marine Components.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The Security Products segment, with a facility in South Carolina and a facility shared with Marine Components in Illinois, manufactures locking mechanisms and other security products for sale to the transportation, postal, office and institutional furniture, cabinetry, tool storage, healthcare and other industries.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our Marine Components segment, with a facility in Wisconsin and a facility shared with Security Products in Illinois, manufactures and distributes stainless steel exhaust systems, gauges and throttle controls primarily for recreational boats.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The chief operating decision maker evaluates segment performance based on segment operating income, which is defined as income before income taxes and interest expense, exclusive of certain general corporate income and expense items (primarily interest income) and certain non-recurring items (such as gains or losses on the disposition of business units and other long-lived assets outside the ordinary course of business).&nbsp;&nbsp;The accounting policies of the reportable operating segments are the same as those described in Note 1. Capital expenditures include additions to property and equipment, but exclude amounts attributable to business combinations.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	F-11
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage37"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU34">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Segment assets are comprised of all assets attributable to the reportable segments
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Corporate assets are not attributable to the operating segments and consist
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	primarily of cash and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ca
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	sh equivalents
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	For geographic information, the point
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	of origin (place of manufacture) for all net sales is the U.S., the point of destination for net sales is based on the location of the customer, and property and equipment are attributable to their physica
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	l location.

	Intersegment sales are not material.

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	F-13
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage39"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 5
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	&#8211;
</FONT>
	Goodwill:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have assigned goodwill to each of our
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	reporting units
</FONT>
	(as that term is defined in ASC Topic 350-20-20,
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Goodwill
</FONT>
	) which correspond to our operating segments.&nbsp;&nbsp;We test for goodwill impairment at the reporting unit level.&nbsp;&nbsp;In accordance with the requirements of ASC Topic 350-20-20, we review goodwill for each of our reporting units for impairment during the third quarter of each year or when circumstances arise that indicate an impairment might be present.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2013 we adopted the guidance in ASU No. 2011-08 for testing goodwill for impairment by assessing qualitative factors to determine whether it is necessary to perform the two-step quantitative goodwill impairment test.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on our qualitative assessment, a quantitative assessment was not required for 2013, 2014, or 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In 2013, 2014 and 2015, goodwill for all applicable reporting units was tested for impairment only in the third quarter of each year in connection with our annual testing date.&nbsp;&nbsp;No impairment was indicated as part of our annual reviews of goodwill.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to 2013, we recorded a $9.9 million goodwill impairment in our Marine Components segment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our gross goodwill at December&#160;31, 2015 is $33.6 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.58%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our current net goodwill balance of $23.7 million was generated from acquisitions relating to Security Products prior to 2001.&nbsp;&nbsp;There have been no changes in the carrying amount of goodwill related to our operations during the past three years.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:12PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We previously had certain U.S. state net operating loss carryforwards, the benefit of which we had not recognized under the more-likely-than-not recognition criteria.&nbsp;&nbsp;We utilized a portion of such state net operating loss carryforward in 2013, and all of the remaining carryforward in 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our provision for income taxes includes a benefit of $102,000 in 2013 and $24,000 in 2014 related to changes in deferred tax asset valuation allowance associated with such carryforwards.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We file income tax returns in U.S. federal and various state and local jurisdictions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our income tax returns prior to 2012 are generally considered closed to examination by applicable tax authorities.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

	F-15

<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	&#8211;

<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Stockholders&#8217; equity:

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Class&#160;A and Class B common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	The shares of Class&#160;A common stock and Class B common stock are identical in all respects, except for certain voting rights and certain conversion rights in respect of the shares of the Class B common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;Holders of Class&#160;A common stock are entitled to one vote per share.&nbsp;&nbsp;NL, which holds all of the outstanding shares of Class B common stock, is entitled to one vote per share in all matters except for election of directors, for which NL is entitled to ten votes per share.&nbsp;&nbsp;Holders of all classes of common stock entitled to vote will vote together as a single class on all matters presented to the stockholders for their vote or approval, except as otherwise required by applicable law.&nbsp;&nbsp;Each share of Class&#160;A common stock and Class B common stock have an equal and ratable right to receive dividends to be paid from our assets when and if declared by the board of directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the event of the dissolution, liquidation or winding up of our operations, the holders of Class&#160;A common stock and Class B common stock will be entitled to share equally and ratably in the assets available for distribution after payments are made to our creditors and to the holders of any of our preferred stock that may be outstanding at the time.&nbsp;&nbsp;Shares of the Class&#160;A common stock have no conversion rights.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under certain conditions, shares of Class B common stock will convert, on a share-for-share basis, into shares of Class&#160;A common stock.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Share repurchases and cancellations.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	Prior to 2013, our board of directors authorized various repurchases of shares of our Class&#160;A common stock in open market transactions, including block purchases, or in privately-negotiated transactions at unspecified prices and over an unspecified period of time.&nbsp;&nbsp;We may repurchase our common stock from time to time as market conditions permit.&nbsp;&nbsp;The stock repurchase program does not include specific price targets or timetables and may be suspended at any time.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depending on market conditions, we may terminate the program prior to its completion.&nbsp;&nbsp;We will generally use cash on hand to acquire the shares.&nbsp;&nbsp;Repurchased shares will be added to our treasury and cancelled.&nbsp;&nbsp;We made no treasury purchases during 2013, 2014 or 2015 and at December&#160;31, 2015, approximately 678,000 shares were available for purchase under these authorizations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Incentive compensation plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	We have a share based incentive compensation plan pursuant to which an aggregate of up to 200,000 shares of our common stock can be awarded to members of our board of directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;All of the Class A common shares we issued in 2013, 2014 and 2015 were issued under this plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;At December&#160;31, 2015, 181,000 shares were available for award under this plan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Dividends.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	In May 2013, our board of directors reduced our regular quarterly dividend from $0.125 per share to $.05 per share, effective with our second quarter 2013 dividend.&nbsp;&nbsp;Declaration and payment of future dividends and the amount thereof, if any, is discretionary and dependent upon our results of operations, financial condition, cash requirements for our businesses, contractual requirements and restrictions and other factors deemed relevant by our board of directors.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:13.08%;TEXT-INDENT:-13.08%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 9
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	&#8211;
</FONT>
	Related party transactions:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU37">
</A>
	We may be deemed to be controlled by Ms. Lisa Simmons and Ms. Serena Connelly.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Note 1. Corporations that may be deemed to be controlled by or affiliated with these individuals sometimes engage in (a)&#160;intercorporate transactions such as guarantees, management and expense sharing arrangements, shared fee arrangements, joint ventures, partnerships, loans, options, advances of funds on open account, and sales, leases and exchanges of assets, including securities issued by both related and unrelated parties and (b)&#160;common investment
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	F-16
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage42"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	and acquisition strategies, business combinations, reorganization
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	s, recapitalizations, securities repurchases, and purchases and sales (and other acquisitions and dispositions) of subsidiaries, divisions or other business units, which transactions have involved both related and unrelated parties and have included transa
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ctions that resulted in the acquisition by one related party of a publicly-held minority equity interest in another related party.&nbsp;&nbsp;We continuously consider, review and evaluate, and understand that Contran and related entities consider, review and evaluat
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	e such transactions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depending upon the business, tax and other objectives then relevant, it is possible that we might be a party to one or more such transactions in the future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	From time to time, we may have loans and advances outstanding between us and various related parties pursuant to term and demand notes.&nbsp;&nbsp;We generally enter into these loans and advances for cash management purposes.&nbsp;&nbsp;When we loan funds to related parties, we are generally able to earn a higher rate of return on the loan than we would earn if we invested the funds in other instruments.&nbsp;&nbsp;While certain of these loans may be of a lesser credit quality than cash equivalent instruments otherwise available to us, we believe we have evaluated the credit risks in the terms of the applicable loans.&nbsp;&nbsp;In this regard, in February 2010 we entered into an unsecured revolving demand promissory note with NL in which, as amended, we agreed to loan NL up to $40 million.&nbsp;&nbsp;As amended, our loans to NL bore interest at the prime rate less .75%, payable quarterly.&nbsp;&nbsp;The principal amount we lent to NL at any time was at our discretion and we made no loans to NL at any time since prior to 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;In June 2015, we terminated such loan facility with NL.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Prior to 2013, we issued a promissory note payable to TIMET Finance Management Company, a former affiliate, which bore interest at LIBOR plus 1% (payable quarterly) and provided for quarterly principal repayments of $250,000 with the balance due at maturity in September 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;The promissory note was prepayable at any time at our option, without penalty, and we prepaid all remaining outstanding principal and interest under this promissory note in July 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;Repayments of principal under this promissory note were $18.5 million in 2013 (including the amount paid upon final payment).&nbsp;&nbsp;We recognized interest expense of $127,000 in 2013 on this promissory note.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Under the terms of an Intercorporate Service Agreement (&#8220;ISA&#8221;) with Contran, employees of Contran perform certain management, tax planning, financial, legal and administrative services for us on a fee basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;Such fees are based upon estimates of time devoted to our affairs by individual Contran employees and the compensation of such persons.&nbsp;&nbsp;Because of the large number of companies affiliated with Contran, we believe we benefit from cost savings and economies of scale gained by not having certain management, financial and administrative staffs duplicated at each entity, thus allowing certain individuals to provide services to multiple companies but only be compensated by one entity.&nbsp;&nbsp;Fees pursuant to these agreements aggregated $3.9 million in 2013 and $3.0 million in 2014 and 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;This agreement is renewed annually, and we expect to pay $3.1 million under the ISA during 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Contran and certain of its subsidiaries and affiliates, including us, purchase certain of their insurance policies as a group, with the costs of the jointly-owned policies being apportioned among the participating companies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Tall Pines Insurance Company (&#8220;Tall Pines&#8221;) and EWI RE, Inc. (&#8220;EWI&#8221;), each subsidiaries of Valhi, provide for or broker certain insurance policies for Contran and certain of its subsidiaries and affiliates, including us.&nbsp;&nbsp;Tall Pines purchases reinsurance from third-party insurance carriers with an A.M.&nbsp;&nbsp;Best Company rating of generally at least A-(Excellent) for substantially all of the risks it underwrites.&nbsp;&nbsp;Consistent with insurance industry practices, Tall Pines and EWI receive commissions from the insurance and reinsurance underwriters and/or assess fees for the policies that they provide or broker.&nbsp;&nbsp;The aggregate premiums we paid to Tall Pines and EWI were approximately $1.0 million in 2013, $1.1 million in 2014 and $1.6 million in 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;These amounts principally represent payments for insurance premiums, which include premiums or fees paid to Tall Pines or fees paid to EWI.&nbsp;&nbsp;These amounts also include payments to insurers or reinsurers through EWI for the reimbursement of claims within our applicable deductible or retention ranges that such insurers or reinsurers paid to third parties on our behalf, as well as amounts for claims and risk management services and various other third-party fees and expenses incurred by the program.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect that these relationships with Tall Pines and EWI will continue in 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU38">
</A>
	With respect to certain of such jointly-owned insurance policies, it is possible that unusually large losses incurred by one or more insureds during a given policy period could leave the other participating companies without adequate coverage under that policy for the balance of the policy period.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result, Contran and certain of its subsidiaries and affiliates, including us, have entered into a loss sharing agreement under which any uninsured loss is shared by those entities who have submitted claims under the relevant policy.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe the benefits in the form
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	F-17
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage43"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	of reduced premiums and broader coverage associated with the group coverage for such policies justifies the risk associated with the potential for any uninsured loss.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:13.08%;TEXT-INDENT:-13.08%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 10
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	&#8211;
</FONT>
	Commitments and contingencies:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Legal proceedings
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are involved, from time to time, in various contractual, product liability, patent (or intellectual property), employment and other claims and disputes incidental to our business.&nbsp;&nbsp;We currently believe the disposition of all claims and disputes, individually or in the aggregate, should not have a material long-term adverse effect on our consolidated financial condition, results of operations or liquidity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Environmental matters and litigation
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our operations are governed by various federal, state and local environmental laws and regulations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our policy is to comply with environmental laws and regulations at all of our facilities and to continually strive to improve environmental performance in association with applicable industry initiatives.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that our operations are in substantial compliance with applicable requirements of environmental laws.&nbsp;&nbsp;From time to time, we may be subject to environmental regulatory enforcement under various statutes, resolution of which typically involves the establishment of compliance programs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Income taxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	From time to time, we undergo examinations of our income tax returns, and tax authorities have or may propose tax deficiencies.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that we have adequately provided accruals for additional income taxes and related interest expense which may ultimately result from such examinations and we believe that the ultimate disposition of all such examinations should not have a material adverse effect on our consolidated financial position, results of operations or liquidity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are a party to a tax sharing agreement with Contran and NL providing for the allocation of tax liabilities and tax payments as described in Note 1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under applicable law, we, as well as every other member of the Contran Tax Group, are each jointly and severally liable for the aggregate federal income tax liability of Contran and the other companies included in the Contran Tax Group for all periods in which we are included in the Contran Tax Group.&nbsp;&nbsp;NL has agreed, however, to indemnify us for any liability for income taxes of the Contran Tax Group in excess of our tax liability in accordance with the tax sharing agreement.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Concentration of credit risk
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our products are sold primarily in North America to original equipment manufacturers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our ten largest customers accounted for approximately 42% of sales in 2013, 47% in 2014, and 48% in 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;United States Postal Service, a customer of the Security Products segment, accounted for 13% of total sales in 2014 and 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Harley Davidson, also a customer of the Security Products segment, accounted for approximately 12%, in 2013, 2014 and 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:10.46%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Rent expense was not significant in 2013, 2014 or 2015 and at December&#160;31, 2015, future minimum rentals under noncancellable operating leases are also not significant.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="CIX-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU39">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
	&#8211;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Recent Accounting Pronouncements:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Adopted
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:5.24%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In November 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-17,
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Income Taxes (Topic 740): Balance Sheet Classification of Deferred Taxes
</FONT>
	, which eliminates the requirement to separate deferred income tax assets and liabilities into current and noncurrent amounts.&#160; Under the ASU all deferred income tax assets and liabilities will be classified as noncurrent.&#160; The current requirement that deferred income tax assets and liabilities of a tax-paying component of an entity be offset and presented as a single amount is not affected by the amendments in this ASU. This amendment is effective for us beginning in the first quarter of 2017; however early adoption is permitted.&#160;&#160; In addition, prospective or retrospective application is permitted.&#160; We have elected to adopt this ASU retrospectively beginning with this Annual Report and accordingly we have presented all deferred income tax assets and liabilities as noncurrent in our Consolidated Balance Sheets and related Footnotes.&#160; At December 31, 2014, we had previously recognized a current deferred income tax asset of $2.4 million and a noncurrent deferred tax income liability of $7.3 million.&#160; As a result of the retrospective application of this ASU, we no longer have a current deferred income tax asset recognized at December 31, 2014, and the net noncurrent deferred income tax liability we now have recognized at December 31, 2014 is $4.9 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Pending Adoption
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:5.24%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In May 2014, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#8220;FASB&#8221;) issued Accounting Standards Update (&#8220;ASU&#8221;) No. 2014-09,
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)
</FONT>
	.&#160; This standard replaces existing revenue recognition guidance, which in many cases was tailored for specific industries, with a uniform accounting standard applicable to all industries and transactions.&#160; The new standard, as amended, is currently effective for us beginning with the first quarter of 2018.&#160; Entities may elect to adopt ASU No. 2014-09 retrospectively for all periods for all contracts and transactions which occurred during the period (with a few exceptions for practical expediency) or retrospectively with a cumulative effect recognized as of the date of adoption.&#160; ASU No. 2014-09 is a fundamental rewriting of existing GAAP with respect to revenue recognition, and we are still evaluating the effect the Standard will have on our Consolidated Financial Statements.&#160; We currently expect to adopt the standard in the first quarter of 2018.&#160; In addition, we have not yet determined the method we will use to adopt the Standard.
</P>
</EFX_NOTES_TO_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT>
